forecastday.title: Monday
forecastday.fcttext: Plentiful sunshine. High near 85F. Winds WNW at 10 to 15 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Sunny. High around 30C. Winds WNW at 15 to 25 km/h.

forecastday.title: Monday Night
forecastday.fcttext: Clear skies. Low 58F. Winds WSW at 10 to 15 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Clear skies. Low 14C. Winds WSW at 15 to 25 km/h.

forecastday.title: Tuesday
forecastday.fcttext: A mainly sunny sky. High 68F. Winds WSW at 10 to 20 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Mainly sunny. High near 20C. Winds WSW at 15 to 30 km/h.

forecastday.title: Tuesday Night
forecastday.fcttext: Clear. Low 56F. Winds W at 10 to 20 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: A mostly clear sky. Low 13C. Winds W at 15 to 30 km/h.

forecastday.title: Wednesday
forecastday.fcttext: Plentiful sunshine. High 72F. Winds WNW at 10 to 15 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Sunshine. High 22C. Winds WNW at 15 to 25 km/h.

forecastday.title: Wednesday Night
forecastday.fcttext: Partly cloudy. Low 58F. Winds NW at 5 to 10 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Partly cloudy. Low around 15C. Winds NW at 10 to 15 km/h.

forecastday.title: Thursday
forecastday.fcttext: A few clouds early, otherwise mostly sunny. High 79F. Winds NW at 10 to 15 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: A few passing clouds, otherwise generally sunny. High 26C. Winds NW at 15 to 25 km/h.

forecastday.title: Thursday Night
forecastday.fcttext: Partly cloudy skies. Low 58F. Winds WNW at 10 to 15 mph.
forecastday.fcttext_metric: Some clouds early will give way to generally clear conditions overnight. Low around 15C. Winds WNW at 15 to 25 km/h.

alerts.message:
...Flash Flood Watch in effect from 3 PM MDT this afternoon through
late tonight...

The National Weather Service in Albuquerque has issued a

* Flash Flood Watch for a portion of north and central New Mexico...
 including the following areas...lower Rio Grande Valley...middle 
 Rio Grande Valley/Albuquerque Metro area...San Francisco River 
 Valley...Southwest Mountains...west Central Highlands...west 
 central mountains and west Central Plateau. 

* From 3 PM MDT this afternoon through late tonight

* moisture from a tropical disturbance will stream over New Mexico
 beginning late this afternoon and continuing through the
 overnight hours. High moisture values combined with lift from
 the disturbance will yield widespread showers and isolated
 thunderstorms. Storms are expected to spread from south to
 north through the period.

* Rainfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches with locally higher amounts
 will be possible between this afternoon and sunrise Tuesday.
 Urban areas as well as areas within and downstream of the
 Whitewater Baldy burn scar will be most susceptible to flash
 flooding.

Precautionary/preparedness actions...

A Flash Flood Watch means that conditions may develop that lead to
flash flooding. Flash flooding is a very dangerous situation.
Monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action should flash
flood warnings be issued.



34
